message: Focus on creating simple cooked combinations first. Cooking raw ingredients (protein, vegetables) increases their value. Combining a cooked protein with a grain or a vegetable often creates a value 40 item. Adding a third distinct component to a 2-component item *can* result in a value 60 item. However, combining items that already have 3 or more distinct base components almost always creates an 'overcomplicated' item with a negative value, which will reset your score to 0. Avoid 'overcomplicating' items. If you have a high-value item, it's safer to submit than risk combining it further, especially if it already has three or more basic components.

Be very cautious with 'overcomplicated' or 'overcooked' features; adding too many items or using the 'stove' on an already cooked item often drops the value significantly, sometimes into the negative. message: Focus on creating sandwiches or simple dishes: 1. Cook raw protein (egg, bacon, fish, beans) with the stove (+20). 2. Combine the cooked protein with a grain (bread, rice, corn, wheat) (+40 total). 3. Add one vegetable (cucumber, beet, broccoli, pepper, potato) to this combination (+60 total). Avoid using the stove on already combined items as this often leads to 'overcooked' and reduces value. Adding too many ingredients can also lead to 'overcomplicated' negative items. Water generally isn't very useful unless you need a 'soaked' component specifically mentioned in a hint.

message: To succeed, follow this pattern: First, combine a raw protein with a raw vegetable. This creates a base item. Second, immediately use the 'stove' tool on this combined item to cook both components; this dramatically increases its value. Third, combine this cooked protein+vegetable item with any raw grain. This will generally bring you to a high score (80). Avoid combining more than three core components (protein, vegetable, grain) and be careful about using the 'stove' on an already cooked item, as this often leads to overcooking and negative values. The 'water' tool can create 'soaked' vegetables, but cooking directly after combining raw protein and vegetable was more consistently valuable.

After that, adding a single 'vegetable' (like tomato, lettuce, or pepper) often further increases the value. Be careful not to 'overcomplicate' items by adding too many ingredients or using the 'stove' on an already combined item, as this can severely drop the value (e.g., to negative scores). The 'water' tool can create 'soaked' ingredients, but these didn't always directly lead to high value in my rounds without further steps.
